Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue on .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `Stop()` → `_thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `SYSLIB0046` (obsolete in .NET 9, unreliable in .NET 8) |
| `Stop()` → `_thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop fallback | **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** — will crash |
| `RunLoop()` → `while(true)` | Cancellable work loop | No way to exit cooperatively |
| `RunLoop()` → `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | Can't be interrupted by cancellation |

## Pre-existing Bug (fixing since it's tightly coupled)

The original has a **race condition**: multiple `Enqueue` calls can fire before `RunLoop` dequeues, but `_newEvent.Reset()` clears the signal after processing only one item, losing the rest until the next enqueue.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wait for a signal OR cancellation — replaces bare WaitOne()
            try
            {
                WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle]);
            }
            catch (ObjectDisposedException)
            {
                break;
            }

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }

            _newEvent.Reset();
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals token.WaitHandle, waking RunLoop
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit — no Abort needed
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop exits cooperatively |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny([event, token.WaitHandle])` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancel signals the wait handle — no need to interrupt |
| `_thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8; cooperative exit replaces it |
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter weight; avoids kernel transition for short waits |

## Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` will crash** — it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`, not `ThreadAbortException`, on .NET 8. This is the #1 reason to migrate.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt` is obsolete** — `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9, and it only works on threads in `WaitSleepJoin` state. Unreliable even on .NET 8.
3. **Don't forget `Dispose`** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed. Always wrap with `IDisposable` or `using`.
4. **Cancellation is cooperative** — if `Handle(item)` is long-running, pass `_cts.Token` into it and check periodically, otherwise `Stop()` blocks until the current item finishes.
5. **Drain the queue** — the inner `while` loop fixes the original signal-loss race. Without it, items pile up and are never processed.
